and":"Lancashire, England"},"en":{"about 1220–circa 1273":"about 1220–about 1273","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1265–1292":"1265–1292","1250–1292":"1250–1292","1220–1273":"1220–1273","1259":"1259","circa 1273":"about 1273","1224":"1224","circa 1250":"1250","1265":"1265","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","about 1220":"about 1220","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","Atherton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Atherton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","Bramber Castle, Sussex, England":"Bramber Castle, Sussex, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lancaster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes de Lancaster was born about 1220, in Lancashire, England. She married Robert William de Atherton about 1273, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1273, in Bramber Castle, Sussex, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1220–circa 1273":"umbes 1220–umbes 1273","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1265–1292":"1265–1292","1250–1292":"1250–1292","1220–1273":"1220–1273","1259":"1259","circa 1273":"umbes 1273","1224":"1224","circa 1250":"1250","1265":"1265","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","Atherton, La